      <div id=3D"divDescription">
         Chord Calculator suggests symbols for chords. Select an entry meth=
od to specify some notes. While Chord Calculator can
         analyze anything from simple triads to complex chords, it is not a=
 substitute for proper chord analysis, which should
         always take <i>context</i> into consideration. It will liberally a=
ccept a wide range of input and do its best to find a
         matching chord symbol, even if there is no third or fifth. Two or =
more notes of unique pitch class constitute a
         =E2=80=9Cchord=E2=80=9D that can be analyzed. The interpretation o=
f input is always literal, as are the results. For
         example, an A7<span class=3D"lp">(</span>=E2=99=AF9<span class=3D"=
rp">)</span> chord has a B=E2=99=AF in it=E2=80=94never a
         C=E2=80=94even though it may be written that way in practice, and =
a dominant 13th will always have all the members
         present (3, 5, =E2=99=AD7, 9, 11, and 13), even though some may be=
 omitted in practice.
      </div>

